&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Oh, you know,

00:12:30.390 --> 00:12:32.890
actually my favorite character
is the honeybee drone.

00:12:32.890 --> 00:12:34.910
Because her name is
Mel and she gets Cruz

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:36.420
out of a lot of trouble.

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:38.150
So, he gets stuck in some places

00:12:38.150 --> 00:12:40.130
and Mel comes along
and saves him.

00:12:40.130 --> 00:12:45.970
My human favorite character
this probably his best friend,

00:12:45.970 --> 00:12:47.270
Lonnie.

00:12:47.270 --> 00:12:49.770
She didn't get accepted into
the academy in the first book,

00:12:49.770 --> 00:12:52.640
so she has to-- they
converse long distance.

00:12:52.640 --> 00:12:54.690
But she helps him out
of a lot of trouble.

00:12:54.690 --> 00:12:57.230
And she also eventually
will be able to make her way

00:12:57.230 --> 00:13:00.120
into the academy, which, you
guys only know that first

00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:01.650
because most people
don't know that.

00:13:01.650 --> 00:13:05.170
Yeah, thank you for
the question.

00:13:05.170 --> 00:13:07.470
Yeah?

00:13:10.310 --> 00:13:13.960
&gt;&gt; What's your favorite
that you created

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:18.610
and is there any competitions?

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:19.910
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Is
there any competitions?

00:13:19.910 --> 00:13:21.210
You mean write the book?

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:25.010
&gt;&gt; No, where do you
get the books?

00:13:25.010 --> 00:13:26.310
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Where
do I get my ideas?

00:13:26.310 --> 00:13:27.610
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:13:27.610 --> 00:13:28.910
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Well, you know,

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:30.630
I get my ideas from
a lot of places.

00:13:30.630 --> 00:13:35.470
I'm really a Star Trek geek
and I love science fiction.

00:13:35.470 --> 00:13:37.190
I love adventure stories.

00:13:37.190 --> 00:13:40.260
And, of course, I
give my inspiration

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:42.460
from the National
Geographic explorers.

00:13:42.460 --> 00:13:44.900
If you go to the National
Geographic's website--

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:50.650
&gt;&gt; My friend Alex, her mom works

00:13:50.650 --> 00:13:53.710
at National Geographic
in Washington, DC.

00:13:53.710 --> 00:13:55.220
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Oh,
that's wonderful.

00:13:55.220 --> 00:14:00.240
&gt;&gt; And one last thing.

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:02.200
Who is your illustrator?

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:06.010
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: My illustrator,
his name is Scott Plumbe.

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:09.860
And he is from Vancouver
British Columbia I think.

00:14:09.860 --> 00:14:11.160
I think he's from Canada.

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:12.460
He's really good.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:13.760
I really like his work.

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:15.520
&gt;&gt; I like mythology.

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:22.150
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Thank
you for your question.

00:14:22.150 --> 00:14:27.090
&gt;&gt; So, what inspired you to
write about the new book?

00:14:27.090 --> 00:14:30.090
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: What
inspired me to write what book?

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:33.890
&gt;&gt; About the book that
you were showing us.

00:14:33.890 --> 00:14:35.190
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit:
What inspired me?

00:14:35.190 --> 00:14:36.490
Well, there's so many things.

00:14:36.490 --> 00:14:38.180
I love adventure stories.

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:41.510
And so, when I was a kid, I used
to read all kinds of adventure.

00:14:41.510 --> 00:14:43.580
I love science fiction.

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:47.840
I love being able to--
I love animals too.

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:51.090
So, it's a great fun
to be able to bring all

00:14:51.090 --> 00:14:53.830
of those things together and
just, you know, have the kids go

00:14:53.830 --> 00:14:56.460
out on an amazing
adventure together and learn

00:14:56.460 --> 00:14:58.940
about the world and
discover new animals.

00:14:58.940 --> 00:15:00.240
I mean, that's so
inspiring to me.

00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:04.070
But what the real National
Geographic explorers do,

00:15:04.070 --> 00:15:06.370
that really inspires me.

00:15:09.390 --> 00:15:13.020
&gt;&gt; The honeybee drone, Mel,

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:17.860
really made me remember
something about drones

00:15:17.860 --> 00:15:23.570
that they are trying to make
as spies, pets for people

00:15:23.570 --> 00:15:29.190
who can't really have
pets, like living animals.

00:15:29.190 --> 00:15:30.990
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit:
Robotics is really huge.

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:35.690
Yeah. And it's amazing what
they're doing in the field

00:15:35.690 --> 00:15:40.110
of drones, robotics,
all the things that--

00:15:40.110 --> 00:15:44.440
I mean, some of the technology
in the book, I used the power

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:45.930
of your mind to do things.

00:15:45.930 --> 00:15:49.270
There is-- they have
mind control cameras.

00:15:49.270 --> 00:15:51.710
So, you put a tiny
little camera in front

00:15:51.710 --> 00:15:54.610
of your eyes then you
take a picture based

00:15:54.610 --> 00:15:56.500
on what you say in your brain.

00:15:56.500 --> 00:15:58.530
We're really actually
not that far away

00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:00.070
from doing things like that.

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:01.950
So that's pretty cool.

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:03.930
Thanks for your question.

00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:08.220
&gt;&gt; Have you ever read a book
about the Galápagos Island?

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:09.820
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: About
what, the Galápagos?

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:11.120
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:12.420
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: You
know, I haven't written

00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:14.360
about the Galápagos islands,
but I have written books

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:20.950
about snakes, alligators,
turtles, reptiles, octopuses.

00:16:20.950 --> 00:16:23.650
My biggest book, one
of my biggest sellers,

00:16:23.650 --> 00:16:25.470
in a book on octopuses.

00:16:25.470 --> 00:16:29.160
They have all this strange,
weird octopuses that are

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:30.460
out there in the world.

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:32.810
So, I love wildlife
and I love nature.

00:16:32.810 --> 00:16:36.240
One of the Explorer Academy
books will be devoted

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:37.540
to ocean life.

00:16:37.540 --> 00:16:38.840
So, they just spend
the whole time

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:40.410
in the ocean under the water.

00:16:40.410 --> 00:16:42.650
And I'm hoping that they
can swim with the turtles

00:16:42.650 --> 00:16:47.420
and have a good time doing that.

00:16:47.420 --> 00:16:48.720
Yeah.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:53.100
&gt;&gt; Well I like reading
Nat Geo kids.

00:16:53.100 --> 00:16:58.070
And I notice some of
your work is in there.

00:16:58.070 --> 00:17:00.750
I read a sneak peek.

00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:02.180
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Thank you.

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:08.470
&gt;&gt; And I'm just wondering,
did you write the bits

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:13.380
for Nat Geo kid's magazine?

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:15.220
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: I
may have had a hand

00:17:15.220 --> 00:17:16.580
in writing a little bit of it.

00:17:16.580 --> 00:17:19.290
I only did an interview
with them, but I think most

00:17:19.290 --> 00:17:23.330
of that was probably
written by the staff,

00:17:23.330 --> 00:17:25.550
may be taking some
things from the book.

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:28.380
We kind of worked together
on some of the items.

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:30.820
But did you-- you saw the
issue where it had all

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:34.860
of the sneak peek of the
Explorer Academy and all that?

00:17:34.860 --> 00:17:36.520
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I really liked that.

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:37.820
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Thank you.

00:17:37.820 --> 00:17:39.400
I hope you like the book too.

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:41.550
Thanks for your question.

00:17:41.550 --> 00:17:45.860
&gt;&gt; What inspired
you to write books?

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:48.080
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: What
inspired me to write books?

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:50.890
I just loved reading as a kid.

00:17:50.890 --> 00:17:54.360
And so, when I was your age,
I read, and read, and read.

00:17:54.360 --> 00:17:57.760
And I used to bring home a stack
of books from the library so big

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:00.230
that I could barely fit
them into my backpack.

00:18:00.230 --> 00:18:02.240
And I always have loved books.

00:18:02.240 --> 00:18:05.150
I didn't always know that
I would write for children.

00:18:05.150 --> 00:18:09.120
But when I got a chance
to go visit classrooms

00:18:09.120 --> 00:18:11.420
as a weather forecaster,
you guys always had

00:18:11.420 --> 00:18:14.410
such great questions, and
you are always so fascinated

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:16.830
and curious, that I just had to.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:18.930
I just had to start
writing for children.

00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:22.300
I just love two write for kids.

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:23.600
Thank you.

00:18:23.600 --> 00:18:25.040
Good question.

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:28.730
&gt;&gt; How long did it take
you to write the book?

00:18:28.730 --> 00:18:30.910
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: It
took about six months.

00:18:30.910 --> 00:18:34.590
And we're releasing a
book every six months.

00:18:34.590 --> 00:18:36.940
So, I have to keep moving.

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:38.980
But the second book
will be out next spring.

00:18:38.980 --> 00:18:41.440
And then the third book will
be out the following fall.

00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:43.520
So, about five to six months.

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:44.820
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:46.620
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Good
question, thanks.

00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:49.650
&gt;&gt; What was your first
book that you wrote?

00:18:49.650 --> 00:18:51.340
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: My first
book was the one that was

00:18:51.340 --> 00:18:55.090
up here called, 'Clouds', that
I showed in the beginning.

00:18:55.090 --> 00:18:57.010
It was all about
different cloud formations

00:18:57.010 --> 00:19:00.070
and how the clouds are formed.

00:19:00.070 --> 00:19:04.490
And then I wrote about three
other books for Scholastic

00:19:04.490 --> 00:19:07.840
on storm chasing and water
cycle and rain, hail,

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:10.950
and snow so that kids who
went to the library to learn

00:19:10.950 --> 00:19:13.340
about weather or if you
wanted to write a report,

00:19:13.340 --> 00:19:15.800
you could check out
one of my books.

00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:17.380
So that was the first
book I ever wrote.

00:19:17.380 --> 00:19:19.730
Then I was hooked.

00:19:19.730 --> 00:19:23.830
&gt;&gt; How did you organize your
ideas for the first book?

00:19:23.830 --> 00:19:25.360
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Good question.

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:29.100
So, what I like to do is, I
like to outline the story.

00:19:29.100 --> 00:19:32.760
And I get an idea, and I
actually where I want each book

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:36.110
to go so that I know throughout
the series what is going

00:19:36.110 --> 00:19:37.410
to happen in every book.

00:19:37.410 --> 00:19:42.150
And then I do a more intense
outline for the first book.

00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:45.730
Kind of where I want it to
start, how I want it to end,

00:19:45.730 --> 00:19:49.610
and then where I want the kids
to be in the middle of the book.

00:19:49.610 --> 00:19:52.170
And then you just sit down
every day and you write.

00:19:52.170 --> 00:19:55.860
And sometimes, the characters
tell you different things,

00:19:55.860 --> 00:19:59.120
they go different places, they
have different ideas than you,

00:19:59.120 --> 00:20:00.420
and I have to let them be

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:01.760
who they are.

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:03.600
But it does help
to have an outline.

00:20:03.600 --> 00:20:06.390
Because then I know where I
want to start and pretty much

00:20:06.390 --> 00:20:11.320
where I want to finish up too.

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:14.510
Thanks for your question.

00:20:14.510 --> 00:20:19.050
&gt;&gt; Did you get tired
of writing books?

00:20:19.050 --> 00:20:20.350
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Did I what?

00:20:20.350 --> 00:20:22.320
&gt;&gt; Get tired of writing books?

00:20:22.320 --> 00:20:23.840
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Tired
of writing-- oh, no.

00:20:23.840 --> 00:20:26.090
I never get tired
of writing books.

00:20:26.090 --> 00:20:28.780
I get tired of other things
like deadlines when I have

00:20:28.780 --> 00:20:32.010
to turn the book in if I
don't get done in time.

00:20:32.010 --> 00:20:33.870
But I never get tired
of writing books.

00:20:33.870 --> 00:20:35.900
I hope I'm writing
books forever.

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:37.200
Yeah, I love books.

00:20:37.200 --> 00:20:41.410
As long as you guys keep
reading, we're good.

00:20:41.410 --> 00:20:43.790
&gt;&gt; How much books do you have?

00:20:43.790 --> 00:20:45.090
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: How
many books do I have?

00:20:45.090 --> 00:20:47.160
I have over 100 books in print.

00:20:47.160 --> 00:20:52.400
I think the Explorer Academy
is 103 but I'm not sure.

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:55.390
I kind of figured I'd
stop counting at 100.

00:20:55.390 --> 00:20:58.440
So, most of them are nonfiction.

00:20:58.440 --> 00:21:01.520
But I have about
nine that are fiction

00:21:01.520 --> 00:21:04.460
and Explorer Academy
is the tenth.

00:21:04.460 --> 00:21:07.840
And I love, like I said, I love
nonfiction, I love learning.

00:21:07.840 --> 00:21:10.810
So, it's great to
be able to do both.

00:21:10.810 --> 00:21:13.800
Good questions.

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:17.360
&gt;&gt; What's your favorite
sea creature?

00:21:17.360 --> 00:21:19.310
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: My
favorite sea creature?

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:25.810
I'm going to go-- it's a tossup
between the Dumbo octopus

00:21:25.810 --> 00:21:27.710
and the Vampire squid.

00:21:27.710 --> 00:21:29.010
But I like them both.

00:21:29.010 --> 00:21:30.420
I like octopuses a lot.

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:32.270
Because they're really smart

00:21:32.270 --> 00:21:35.020
and they're clever
and they're creative.

00:21:35.020 --> 00:21:40.100
And when I was doing my book on
octopuses-- I'm from Seattle.

00:21:40.100 --> 00:21:42.550
And I went to a Seattle aquarium
and I talked to a biologist.

00:21:42.550 --> 00:21:45.880
And he told me just how
smart the octopuses were

00:21:45.880 --> 00:21:47.180
at the aquarium.

00:21:47.180 --> 00:21:49.470
He said that they had
an octopus name Clyde.

00:21:49.470 --> 00:21:53.080
And they noticed that
the other exhibits

00:21:53.080 --> 00:21:55.750
around Clyde seemed
to be disappearing.

00:21:55.750 --> 00:21:59.290
The other fish and
the crab were missing.

00:21:59.290 --> 00:22:00.940
And they put a camera on Clyde

00:22:00.940 --> 00:22:04.190
and they realized Clyde was
leaving his exhibit at night

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:06.510
and going into the other
exhibits and eating them.

00:22:06.510 --> 00:22:11.490
And that's when I realized that
these animals are really cool.

00:22:11.490 --> 00:22:14.370
They're very clever,
they're very smart.

00:22:14.370 --> 00:22:16.000
They can open jars.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:20.270
My sister is a diver
and she went diving once

00:22:20.270 --> 00:22:23.830
and an octopus came along
and took her flashlight

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:25.400
and swam away with it.

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:26.920
She never saw it again.

00:22:26.920 --> 00:22:28.530
It just went away.

00:22:28.530 --> 00:22:30.280
So, I love octopuses a lot.

00:22:30.280 --> 00:22:33.990
I have to figure out a way to
get them into Explorer Academy.

00:22:33.990 --> 00:22:35.710
So, I have a couple
minutes left.

00:22:35.710 --> 00:22:37.710
Are there more questions?

00:22:37.710 --> 00:22:40.790
&gt;&gt; What's your favorite
part about creating a book?

00:22:40.790 --> 00:22:42.090
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit:
My favorite part

00:22:42.090 --> 00:22:44.200
about creating a book really
is starting with page one.

00:22:44.200 --> 00:22:45.760
I love a blank page.

00:22:45.760 --> 00:22:48.840
Because at that point,
you can do anything.

00:22:48.840 --> 00:22:51.070
You can have the
characters go anywhere,

00:22:51.070 --> 00:22:54.110
say anything, do anything.

00:22:54.110 --> 00:22:57.080
And it's exciting to me
to write that first page.

00:22:57.080 --> 00:22:58.380
I love that part.

00:22:58.380 --> 00:23:01.490
The hardest part-- because I bet
you're going to ask that too--

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:03.590
is ending a series
or ending a book.

00:23:03.590 --> 00:23:05.290
It's hard to say
goodbye to characters

00:23:05.290 --> 00:23:07.950
that you spent so
much time with.

00:23:07.950 --> 00:23:09.800
Good questions, you guys.

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:11.100
Yeah?

00:23:11.100 --> 00:23:12.900
&gt;&gt; What's your favorite
book you've made?

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:14.200
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit:
My favorite book?

00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:16.280
Well, I have to say
Explorer Academy.

00:23:16.280 --> 00:23:17.580
Usually the book
that I'm working

00:23:17.580 --> 00:23:19.180
on now is my favorite book.

00:23:19.180 --> 00:23:21.220
And I love Explorer Academy

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:23.540
because it combines all the
things that I love to do.

00:23:23.540 --> 00:23:27.040
In nonfiction and fiction,
and adventure and science.

00:23:27.040 --> 00:23:29.740
It's a perfect combination
for me.

00:23:29.740 --> 00:23:32.090
I love doing Explorer Academy.

00:23:33.580 --> 00:23:36.290
&gt;&gt; What inspired
you to write books?

00:23:36.290 --> 00:23:38.450
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: So many things.

00:23:38.450 --> 00:23:40.980
I just really enjoy words.

00:23:40.980 --> 00:23:43.020
I enjoyed telling stories.

00:23:43.020 --> 00:23:46.300
My parents can tell you I
was telling them stories

00:23:46.300 --> 00:23:47.640
when I was really young,

00:23:47.640 --> 00:23:49.520
and they were really
tired of hearing it.

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:51.560
But I just love storytelling.

00:23:51.560 --> 00:23:53.220
I love reading.

00:23:53.220 --> 00:23:58.430
And to be able to do an
adventure series is so exciting.

00:23:58.430 --> 00:24:01.490
I'm, you know, thrilled
to be able to do that.

00:24:01.490 --> 00:24:02.840
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:24:02.840 --> 00:24:04.140
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit:
You're very welcome.

00:24:04.140 --> 00:24:05.440
Thank you.

00:24:05.440 --> 00:24:08.170
&gt;&gt; What challenges did you
face writing this book?

00:24:08.170 --> 00:24:09.470
&gt;&gt; Trudi Trueit: Good question.

00:24:09.470 --> 00:24:12.410
There were a lot of challenges
in writing an adventure

00:24:12.410 --> 00:24:16.520
because you want it to be fast
paced, really interesting.

00:24:16.520 --> 00:24:19.850
You want them to go
through a lot of challenges.

00:24:19.850 --> 00:24:21.150
But at the same time,
you want to be able

00:24:21.150 --> 00:24:22.580
to develop the characters too

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:25.120
and have good relationships
and good friendships.

00:24:25.120 --> 00:24:29.060
So, yeah, it is, at times it
can be a challenge to make sure

